System Calls

Zilogic Systems

Introduction

Kernel

  • The kernel is the software component that enables sharing of resources in the system.
  • Applications running on a system need to share the CPU, Memory, Disk, Network Interface, etc.
  • Kernel creates high level entities that enable controlled sharing of these resources.
  • High level entities - processes, files, sockets, etc.

Processes

  • Bundle of code and run-time state.
  • Kernel time multiplexes the CPU between processes.
  • Kernel allocates a virtual address space to each process.
  • Processes allow the CPU and memory to be shared.
  • Syscalls: exec(), fork(), wait(), kill(), etc.

Files

  • Files allows the disk to be shared.
  • Each application can write to a separate file on the same disk, without interfering with each other.
  • Syscalls: open(), read(), write(), close(), etc.

Sockets

  • Sockets allows the network to be shared.
  • Each application can communicate over the network, using a separate socket, without interfering with each other.
  • Syscalls: socket(), send(), recv(), etc.

Kernel and Syscalls

  • With bare hardware, we can work with instructions, memory locations, hard disk sectors.
  • But with the OS kernel running on the hardware, we are provided with higher level entities like files, processes, sockets, etc.
  • The kernel provides functions to create and manipulate these entities. These functions are called system calls.

Mapping the Kernel

Process Memory Map

  • Every process is associated with instructions to execute (code) and global data, stack and heap (data).
  • The kernel also has associated code and data.
  • The process has to execute functions inside the kernel to manipulate the abstractions provided by the kernel - files, processes, sockets and other resources.

Process Memory Map (Contd.)

Process Memory Map (Contd.)

1GB/3GB Split

  • The top 3GB of virtual address space is used for the mapping the user code and data and the bottom 1GB of virtual address space is used for mapping the kernel code and data.
  • When the scheduler switches between various processes the mapping for top 3GB of virtual address will keep switching to the corresponding process code and data, but the bottom 1GB will be always mapped to the same kernel code and data.

Problems

    do_open(filename, flags, mode);

Problem 2: Privileges

  • Kernel - manages and shares resources
    • CPU - Scheduler
    • Memory - Memory Management Subsystem
  • User space process
    • Disable Interrupts
    • Modify the Page Tables

Solution

Hardware Privilege Levels

  • The hardware provides the following features to overcome this.
    1. Protection Modes
    2. System pages
    3. Mechanism to switch to System Mode

Protection Modes

  • The processor can operate in two protection mode - System and User.
  • In sytem mode, the processor can execute any instruction, and can access any memory location.
  • In User mode, the processor cannot execute certain instructions, and cannot access certain memory locations. For example the processor cannot execute instructions that modify the page tables.
  • The kernel code executes in Sytem Mode, and user code executes in User Mode.

System Pages

  • The page table has a flag that indicates whether a page is a System page.
  • System pages can be accessed only when the processor is in System Mode.
  • User pages can be accessed when the processor is in either System Mode or User Mode.
  • The pages corresponding to user code and data are indicated as User pages.
  • The pages corresponding to kernel code and data are indicated as System pages.

System Pages (Contd)

System Pages (Contd)

Entering System Mode

  • The processor switches to System Mode under only one circumstance - when an interrupt occurs.
  • When an interrupt occurs the processor switches to System Mode and transfers control to a preset address.
  • The preset address generally contains kernel code that handles the interrupts.

Traps

  • Interrupts can occur due to hardware devices asserting the interrupt line - these are called hardware interrupts.
  • Interrupts can also be triggered using an instruction, these are called software interrupts or traps.
  • When a trap is executed, the processor switches to System Mode and transfers control to a preset address.

Implementing System Calls

  • Each system call is given a unique no.
  • A system call table, maps system call no. to system calls within the kernel.
  • To be more accurate, the system call table is an array of function pointers.

Implementing System Calls

  • When the user process wants to execute a system call, it stores the system call no. in a specific CPU register and triggers a software interrupt.

Implementing System Calls

  • The processor switches to System Mode, and starts executing the trap handler. The trap handler is part of the kernel code.
  • The trap handler uses the system call no. to invoke the specified system call.

Implementing System Calls

  • On return from system call, the control is transferred back to the process that invoked the system call.

Problems Revisited

  • Applications cannot access kernel code and data.
  • Applications cannot do priviledged operations.
  • But applications can request the kernel to perform actions on its behalf.
  • Kernel checks if the application has required permissions to do so, before performing the action.
  • Thus we are able achieve controlled access to the system calls, through the hardware privilege levels and the trap mechanism.

Kernel: Another Perspective

How the Kernel Works

  • Kernel unlike a process is not continuously executing.
  • Kernel is rather a bundle of interrupt handlers.
  • It only executes when an interrupt occurs.
  • The kernel is invoked either due to a hardware interrupt - timer interrupt, page fault, etc.
  • Or if the process invokes a system call, by executing a trap instruction
